{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:50:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:50:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14737"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14737"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.1,0.1,0.43,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65193"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7430"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50630"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5190"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21664"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65193"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAttention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is commonly treated with medications that affect catecholamine neurotransmission in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of methylphenidate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Selectively inhibits noradrenaline reuptake","Blocks serotonin reuptake","Increases dopamine receptor sensitivity","Blocks dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake","Antagonises dopamine receptors"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of methylphenidate is \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E in the central nervous system. This increases the concentration of these neurotransmitters in the synaptic cleft, improving attention and reducing hyperactivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelectively inhibits noradrenaline reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes medications like atomoxetine, which are second-line treatments for ADHD\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks serotonin reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors used in depression, not ADHD\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases dopamine receptor sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a mechanism of any current ADHD medications\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises dopamine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes antipsychotic medications which would worsen ADHD symptoms by reducing dopaminergic transmission\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy blocking both dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake, methylphenidate enhances catecholamine signalling in brain regions involved in attention, executive function, and impulse control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Methylphenidate works by blocking both dopamine and noradrenaline reuptake transporters in the central nervous system.","Increased synaptic concentrations of dopamine and noradrenaline improve attention and reduce hyperactivity in ADHD.","Methylphenidate differs from selective reuptake inhibitors by affecting both dopamine and noradrenaline systems simultaneously."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australasian ADHD Professionals Association. 5.2 Medication Choice - ADHD Guideline. Accessed 31 October, 2024. Available from: https://adhdguideline.aadpa.com.au/pharmacological/medication/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14737"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:14:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:22:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7430"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65193"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i